BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:Profs & Pints Napa: The Dirt on White-Collar Crime
DTSTART;TZID=America/Los_Angeles:20260414T180000
DTEND;TZID=America/Los_Angeles:20260414T203000
UID:260405hQQepsY6BEyEKKUoax8BIw
DESCRIPTION:Profs and Pints Napa presents: **“The Dirt on White-Collar 
 Crime\,”** a debunking of the myths and examination of the realities su
 rrounding “nonviolent\,” financially motivated misdeeds\, with Bryan B
 urton\, associate professor of criminology and criminal justice at Sonoma 
 State University and researcher of white-collar crime\, corporate crime\, 
 and regulation.\n\nThe public’s understanding of white-collar crime is s
 haped less by empirical research than by powerful myths. Such myths distor
 t our ideas about what constitutes normal or acceptable behavior as well a
 s our assumptions about the harm caused by white-collar crime and our thou
 ghts about who is responsible for it and how perpetrators should be held a
 ccountable.\n\nBe on hand as Bryan Burton\, a scholar of crime and crimina
 l justice in the United States and abroad\, shines light on the reality su
 rrounding illegal misdeeds that get termed “white-collar.”  \n\nHe
 ’ll start by challenging an assumption that’s ingrained in the very de
 finition of white-collar crime\, the idea that it’s somehow “nonviolen
 t.” We’ll look at how the unsafe consumer products\, hazardous workpla
 ces\, environmental contamination\, and corporate negligence associated wi
 th white-collar and corporate crime often result in serious injury\, illne
 ss\, and death.\n\nProfessor Burton also will debunk the myth that white-c
 ollege crime is somehow less costly than conventional street crime\, showi
 ng how the financial and social costs of white-collar offenses often far e
 xceed those associated with conventional street offenses. \n\nHe’ll sha
 tter the notion that we can rely on regulatory agencies to protect us from
  serious white-collar misdeeds\, describing how regulatory enforcement is 
 hindered by political pressures and resource constraints. As part of this 
 discussion\, he’ll look at the phenomenon of regulatory capture\, when i
 ndependent watchdog agencies become overly influenced by\, and end up adva
 ncing the interests of\, the industries or groups they were established to
  oversee.\n\nFinally\, he’ll take on the cynical beliefs that nothing ca
 n be done about white-collar crime or that white-collar offenders are some
 how untouchable. He’ll explain why accountability for white-collar crime
  is often uneven.\n\nWe’ll look at practical ways that society\, organiz
 ations\, and audience members as individuals can work to fight white-colla
 r crime and reduce its harms. You’ll leave feeling wiser and more empowe
 red to keep yourself from being victimized. (Tickets available only online
 . Advance tickets: $13.50 plus processing fees. Doors: $17\, or $15 with a
  student ID. Doors open at 5:30 and the talk begins at 6:30.)\n\nImage by 
 Canva
LOCATION:Napa Yard
URL:https://events.ticketleap.com/tickets/profsandpints/the-dirt-on-white-
 collar-crime
X-SOURCE:Press Democrat
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:Cumbia with Mireille
DTSTART;TZID=America/Los_Angeles:20260414T180000
DTEND;TZID=America/Los_Angeles:20260414T190000
UID:260401SD6cNIARekSvOJo03ymIhw
DESCRIPTION:Feel the Rhythm with Cumbia\n\nReady to master the “Step of 
 the Soul”? Join us for a high-energy cumbia class where we dive into the
  heart of Latin America’s most infectious dance. Whether you have two le
 ft feet or you’re a dance floor regular\, this class will get you moving
  with confidence.\n\nMireille will guide you through:\n\nBasic directional
  steps: The signature back-break basic step\, essential turns\, and the 
 “Guacharaca” rhythm.\n\nThe Vibe: No partner required\, no experience
  necessary—just bring your energy and a pair of comfortable shoes!\n\nIm
 portant Details\n\nNo dance experience required: Whether you’ve never d
 anced before or it’s been a while\, you’re welcome here!\n\nNo partner
  necessary: Come solo or bring a friend—either way\, you’ll have plen
 ty of opportunities to dance.\n\nPlease wear non-marking shoe soles: Thi
 s helps us keep our dance floor in great condition.\n\nCome join us and di
 scover the joy of cumbia. We can’t wait to see you on the dance floor.\n
 \nDate & Time: Tuesdays \, 6:00 pm\n\nInstructor: Mireille Ruiz Born an
 d raised in Mexico City\, she grew up dancing and listening to Latin Music
  as part of her culture including Cumbia\, Banda\, ranchera\, quebradita\,
  etc. she learned her first following Techniques\, dancing with her father
  in every family fiesta. she has a background in Mexican folklore\, Jazz\,
  tap dancing and gymnastics\, she also is a percussionist\, drummer and Mo
 ntessori Teacher.\n\nShe grew up performing since she the age of 4. Bay Ar
 ea bachata and cumbia dance instructor\, Mireille has been teaching dance\
 , performing\,  leading dance teams\, around USA events\, dance festival
 s\, congresses since 2008\n\nAddress: 4140 Redwood Highway \\#8 San Rafael
 \, CA\n\nNote: Arrive 10 minutes before. No floor marking shoe soles allow
 ed.
LOCATION:Salsa Dance Marin
URL:https://www.pressdemocrat.com/events/#/details/cumbia-with-mireille/18
 336616/2026-04-14T18
X-SOURCE:Press Democrat
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:INTO THE LIGHT: Light-filled aintings by Katy Boggs
DTSTART;TZID=America/Los_Angeles:20260414T100000
DTEND;TZID=America/Los_Angeles:20260414T170000
UID:260330R8EOqF5RkkmKv4TnXtM1cg
DESCRIPTION:Katy's paintings are an exploration of light—how it shapes f
 orm\, reveals color\, and defines what we see.\n\n"I am drawn to moments w
 here light is felt as much as seen: filtering through dense leaves\, tower
 ing in the crowns of trees\, glinting off cresting waves\, or softening in
 to the quiet glow of a sunset. Light is everywhere\; without it\, there is
  no seeing. Beyond its physical presence\, it also carries a deeper resona
 nce as a symbol of hope. In a time of uncertainty\, this work seeks to bri
 ng light into the image\, both visually and metaphorically."\n\nReception:
  April 25\, 4 to 6 pm.
LOCATION:Sebastopol Gallery
URL:http://sebastopolgallery.com
X-SOURCE:Press Democrat
END:VEVENT
