BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:Patron Saints of Influence Spring Reading & Open Mic
DTSTART;TZID=America/Los_Angeles:20260426T160000
DTEND;TZID=America/Los_Angeles:20260426T180000
UID:260319imfMD9luq0qAiRiyLC6xSQ
DESCRIPTION:The next Patron Saints of Influence quarterly literary reading
  & open mic on Sunday\, April 26 will pay homage to the poet\, musician\, 
 and political activist Gil Scott-Heron with featured readings by Yume Kim\
 , Steve Shain\, and Grayson Thompson. Find us at Shady Oak Barrel House in
  Santa Rosa starting at 4PM.\n\nAs always\, you are also welcome to share 
 some of your own written work in 5 minutes or less during the open mic \\(
 arrive early to sign up\\). That could include song lyrics or spoken word 
 if you're especially inspired by Gil Scott-Heron\, but all words are welco
 me as long as they're not hateful.\n\nAbout the Featured Readers:\n\nYume 
 Kim is a poet\, educator\, and author of Reserve the Right. In 2011\, she 
 moved from her home state Virginia to California for her graduate studies 
 at San Francisco State University. There\, she earned both an M.A. in Engl
 ish and an M.F.A. in Creative Writing. Additionally\, she is a recipient o
 f the following fellowships: Kundiman \\(June 2012\\)\, The Ruby Creatives
  in Residence \\(2022-2023\\)\, and The Bay Area Writing Project Invitatio
 nal Summer Institute \\(June 2024\\). Some of her works can also be found 
 in the following journals: gesture\, sPARKLE \\+ bLINK\, West Wind Review\
 , Transfer\, Sugared Water\, Writing Without Walls\, The Bangalore Review\
 , You Might Need to Hear This\, and The Sad Girls Lit Club.\n\nSteve Shain
 's journey with the voice of the bass began in 1963 in Chicago Heights\, I
 ll. Since being introduced to beat generation poet ruth weiss by painter P
 aul Beattie in 1984\, Steve has usually been seen accompanying poets throu
 ghout the Bay Area. Most recently\, Steve’s own verbiage is being shared
 \; a unique/personal perspective on a life lived\, from a survivor/observe
 r/commentator. The voice of Steve’s bass is special\, too: a 1930s Alcoa
  made in Buffalo\, NY\, Dura \\(the bass\\) speaks: not jazz/not classical
 /not bluegrass but “BASSICNESS” … inherent tones & rhythms dictated 
 by inspiration and the present tense. His teachers include Florence Danger
 mond\, Nancy McCain\, Edward Krolick\, Curtis Burris\, and Glen Moore. His
  muse-ical mentors include Ron Crotty\, Darrell DeVore\, Richard Waters\, 
 and Harry Partch. He has also shared stages with ruth weiss\, Jack Micheli
 ne\, Lawrence Ferlinghetti\, Eugene Ruggles\, Sherrill Milnes\, Eugene Ist
 omin\, Earl LeClaire\, and David Best\; and recorded with Leopard Set\, To
 m Waits\, and others. When not playing bass\, Steve can be found as propri
 etor of “bassic sewing”\, a Santa Rosa leather fabrication & repair sh
 op.\n\nGrayson Thompson \\[he/him\\] is a Black\, Jamaican-American\, quee
 r transgender cowboy poet who moonlights as a therapist. He is the inaugur
 al Slam Poetry Champion of Santa Rosa\, CA. A mouthful\, Grayson is Foglif
 ter Press' 2024 Start A Riot! Chapbook Prize Winner with SAND BODIED FLORI
 DA BOY and Winner of Write Bloody Publishing's 2024 Jack McCarthy Book Pri
 ze for his full-length collection\, A CONGREGATION OF ALLIGATORS \\(Septem
 ber 2025\\). Born in Massachusetts\, raised between Florida and New Englan
 d\, Grayson’s work centers the body and its relationship to the prerequi
 sites needed for social existence…to be recognized by others as being hu
 man. His poems explore race\, queerness\, and gender\; family\, grief\, an
 d grace.
LOCATION:Shady Oak Barrel House
URL:http://tinyurl.com/patron-saints-form
X-SOURCE:Press Democrat
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:Edible & Medicinal Plant Walk
DTSTART;TZID=America/Los_Angeles:20260426T100000
DTEND;TZID=America/Los_Angeles:20260426T130000
UID:26031946iEthirZk2o54dX4BnveQ
DESCRIPTION:Weaving in natural history\, ethnobotany\, herbalism and
  folktales\, this walk will open your senses\, as well as your
  curiosity to the abundance of plantlore in Sonoma County.\n\nTic
 kets are $15 for adults\, $7.5 for youth \\(12-17 year olds\; a
 ll children under 18 must be accompanied by a parent or legal 
 guardian\\)\, students\, Sugarloaf members\, and Sugarloaf or RFO 
 volunteers\, and free for children under 12. Meet at the White 
 Barn parking lot. Bring at least a quart of water and a lunch
  and be prepared for a leisurely 2-3 mile walk with a 250-ft 
 climb. Wear layers\, appropriate footwear for slippery \\(and poss
 ibly muddy\\) terrain\, and sun protection. Heavy rains cancel\; 
 parking fees apply.\n\nEdible plant information is for educational
  purposes only. Foraging is illegal in CA State Parks.
LOCATION:Sugarloaf Ridge State Park
URL:https://www.pressdemocrat.com/events/#/details/edible-medicinal-plant-
 walk/18346220/2026-04-26T10
X-SOURCE:Press Democrat
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:Art Exhibit: The Poetic Landscape
DTSTART;TZID=America/Los_Angeles:20260426T110000
DTEND;TZID=America/Los_Angeles:20260426T180000
UID:260318Rq_djMSqSU6bd17HyuS2JQ
DESCRIPTION:Date: FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE  3/13/26\n\nAPRIL EXHIBIT: THE PO
 ETIC LANDSCAPE\n\nEXHIBIT DATES:  March 30  – April 26\, 2026\n\nRECEP
 TION: SATURDAY\, APRIL 4\, 2026\, 3-5 pm: Join us to meet KAREN MILLER and
  PHYLLIS RAPP\;  celebrate the show and enjoy a poetry reading by feature
 d guest\, Linda Loveland Reid\, gallery artist and published author.  Be 
 sure to take part in the Gallery’s free monthly drawing for a beautiful 
 work by a Gallery artist.  Refreshments will be served.\n\nSonoma County 
 artist\, Karen Miller\, presents The Poetic Landscape\, pastel paintings t
 hat convey Miller’s personal experience in connecting with the intrinsic
  beauty of natural places. In these pieces\, color\, fluid shapes and rhyt
 hmic design combine to create an uplifting mood – a true poetic interlud
 e.  Evoking a happy mood\, “Geyserville Sunflowers\,” turning to the 
 sun by nature\, joyfully dance in its luminescence. By the river’s edge\
 , concentric reflections conjure a calm sense of wellbeing in “Fetch.”
   The viewer feels welcomed by a warm embrace entering a shaded secret sp
 ot in “September Trellis.”  Focused on local scenes\, these works tru
 ly hone in on the stunning landscape out our doors.  Miller remarked “ 
 As I contemplate the very real places of beauty surrounding us\, I try to 
 express my painterly response in hopes it will engender recognition by the
  viewers.” \n\nMeet the artist: Miller will be hosting the Gallery on M
 arch 30\, April 5 & 15 from 11am to 2:30 pm.\n\n The Stairway Smallworks 
 Showcase features Phyllis Rapp’s Magic Moments\, a collection of waterco
 lors that create an atmosphere that is both introspective and magical.  F
 amiliar domestic scenes are transformed as humans interact with animals an
 d birds in floral settings.  In “Silent Watcher” the red-headed young
  woman’s green eyes lock onto ours as she stares ahead\, flanked by her 
 avian companion.  Experiencing these works is a like taking a mini-step o
 n the wild side\, an exciting and fun experience.\n\nMeet the artist: Rapp
  will be hosting the Gallery on March 30 and April 10 from 11am to 6 pm.\n
 \nAlso join us for ART NITE HEALDSBURG\, Thursday\, April 2\, 5 – 6 pm.
   The theme for the 2026 kickoff event is Bouquets to Art.  ART NITE Hea
 ldsburg\, held the 1st Thursday of Every Month\, is a community event cele
 brating art and creativity with over 20 galleries participating.  ArtNite
 Healdsburg.com.\n\nUpstairs Art Gallery\, 306 Center Street\, Healdsburg\,
  CA 95448. \\(707\\) 431-4214.: OPEN DAILY: 11am – 6 pm.    www.upsta
 irsart gallery.net \n\nFor further information: Contact: Beverly Bird\, Pr
 ess Contact\, at bvdrio@sonic.net or 707-799-1490.
LOCATION:Upstairs Art Gallery
URL:http://www.upstairsartgallery.net
X-SOURCE:Press Democrat
END:VEVENT
