BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:Old Wine\, New Bottle
DTSTART;TZID=America/Los_Angeles:20260426T160000
DTEND;TZID=America/Los_Angeles:20260426T180000
UID:260129AGF3NiEVRUuPSgeW9R_a2A
DESCRIPTION:What if Mozart’s music could surprise you with new colors yo
 u didn’t know you were missing? This program shines a spotlight on two o
 f his favorite voices: the basset horn and the basset clarinet. Deeper\, w
 armer\, and more velvety than their modern descendants\, these instruments
  were prized in Mozart’s time for their ability to sing\, sigh\, and whi
 sper with uncanny intimacy.\n\nThe program begins with a charming quintet 
 by Mozart’s contemporary Johann Backofen\, whose writing shows off the b
 asset horn’s mellow glow and conversational wit. Mozart’s youthful “
 Milanese” string quartet follows\, sparkling with elegance and invention
 . The program culminates in Mozart’s beloved clarinet quintet\, a work o
 f timeless beauty\, virtuosity\, and ingenuity performed here on a replica
  of the original basset clarinet Mozart had in mind. Performed on period i
 nstruments\, this concert offers a chance to hear familiar music scrubbed 
 clean—lighter\, more transparent\, and irresistibly alive.
LOCATION:The Moon House
URL:https://musicinplace.org/event/old-wine-new-bottle/
X-SOURCE:Press Democrat
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:Por la Luz de la Luna: A Mexican Ballet
DTSTART;TZID=America/Los_Angeles:20260426T130000
DTEND;TZID=America/Los_Angeles:20260426T150000
UID:260401xzQAthzSok2f1-trhcnRcg
DESCRIPTION:This original ballet libretto was inspired by award-winning au
 thor and arts activist Aida Salazar's story of her great-aunt\, Jovita Val
 dovinos\, who fought for religious freedom in Mexico's Cristero War in the
  1930s.Por la Luz de la Lunabrings a fictional account of Jovita's story t
 o life\, weaving history\, mythology\, and family legacy into a powerful t
 heatrical experience while celebrating her heroism. As one of the few Mexi
 can-themed ballets in history\, it creates a space for dancers of all back
 grounds to portray Latina/o characters\, highlighting unique stories and h
 onoring Mexican and Mexican-American heritage on stage. Set to 20th-centur
 y Mexican classical music by composers such as Carlos Chávez and José Pa
 blo Moncayo\, the ballet is brought to life through striking sets and Azte
 c-inspired costumes designed by visual artist PEMEX. It premiered on April
  9\, 2016\, at the Sebastiani Theatre and continues to be a highlight of t
 he company's repertory.
URL:https://creativesonoma.org/event/por-la-luz-de-la-luna-a-mexican-balle
 t/
X-SOURCE:Press Democrat
END:VEVENT
